  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving Water Management and Sanitation facilities with a gender approach in Nicaragua</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is focused on Water Resources Management with Women&#x2019;s Empowerment. CAFOD&#x2019;s partner ASOMUPRO will work in communities located in a dry corridor, which is characterized by little rainfall and long dry periods.

The Mozonte people are affected by the consumption of polluted water - research found arsenic and faecal traces in underground water. The majority of people do not implement good hygiene practices and do not use chlorine. Other problems are related to the management of waste water and lack of latrines. Many families are not using good hygiene practices due to ignorance and a lack of infrastructure to collect garbage and polluted containers in the rural areas where pesticides are heavily used; therefore farmers burn the garbage in the best case. 

Through (a) training on water management principles and practice, and on health and hygiene; and (b) the construction of rainwater tanks and sewage management ponds, the project will work with the community members &#x2013; principally female-headed households - to improve environmental and health practices, including management of waste water, construction of sanitation structures, awareness raising of preventative health practices, water and soil conservation.
 
In addition, training sessions on gender policy and practice will result in female-headed households having improved quality of life; will promote and enhance women&#x2019;s participation during project implementation; and improve project sustainability.</narrative>
  </description>
